  "bib_entries": {
    "54823849": {
      "title": "Simple singularities and topology of symplectically filling 4-manifold",
      "abstract": "Topological restrictions of symplectically filling 4-manifolds of links around simple singularities are studied by using the Seiberg-Witten monopole equations. In particular, the intersection form of minimal symplectically filling 4-manifolds of the singularity of type E 8 is determined. Moreover, for the case of simply elliptic singularities, similar restrictions are obtained. In the proof, a vanishing theorem of the Seiberg-Witten invariant is discussed."
    },
    "123173346": {
      "title": "Taut foliations in punctured surface bundles",
      "abstract": "this model, a given fibration can be perturbed to give 'nearby' fibrations. In this paper, we describe an alternative way of perturbing fibrations with non- empty boundary. Instead of fibrations, this construction yields taut foliations very closely related to the original fibration but with different boundary behaviour. Given M with torus boundary component T, and assigned coordinate system for T, we say that a fibration or taut foliation F realizes ¶-slope r on T ifF intersects T in simple curves of slope r. (When F is a fibration, r is necessarily rational. In general, however, we assume only that r is real.) When a compact, orientable, fibred manifold M has a single boundary component, exactly one ¶-slope is realized by fibrations. However, the closely related taut foliations realize a non-empty interval of ¶-slopes. In § 4, we prove the following theorem. Theorem 4.1. Given an orientable, fibred, compact 3-manifold with single boundary component, a fibration with fibre surface of negative Euler charac- teristic can be perturbed to yield taut foliations realizing an open interval of boundary slopes about the boundary slope of the fibration. Remark. When M is fibred with fibre a once-punctured torus, the taut foliations realized are those of (11) in different guise. As corollary, we have information about manifolds obtained by performing Dehn surgery along slopes sufficiently close to the slope of a fibre. Such manifolds necessarily contain taut foliations. Hence, by Novikov (16), they are irreducible with infinite fundamental group. By Palmeira (20), they have universal cover R 3 . In certain cases, it is possible to say precisely what 'sufficiently close' means; that is, to identify the interval realized. In (11), Hatcher does this for the once-punctured torus bundles over S 1 .I n (23), we describe the intervals for once-punctured surface bundles in terms of their Gabai degeneracy. In § 5, we begin an investigation of generalizations of the construction. We give an analogous result for manifolds containing a taut foliation with compact leaf a punctured surface of positive genus and possessing a non-separating comple- mentary product disc. (See § 5.) Then, for those readers familiar with essential laminations, we show that if M contains an essential spanning surface S with non-separating complementary product disc, then S can be perturbed to yield"
    },
    "11374897": {
      "title": "Holomorphic disks and genus bounds",
      "abstract": "We prove that, like the Seiberg-Witten monopole homology, the Heegaard Floer homology for a three-manifold determines its Thurston norm. As a consequence, we show that knot Floer homology detects the genus of a knot. Thisleads to new proofs of certain results previously obtained using Seiberg-Witten monopole Floer homology (in collaboration with Kronheimer and Mrowka). It also leads to a purely Morse-theoretic interpretation of the genus of a knot. The method of proof shows that the canonical element of Heegaard Floer homology associated to a weakly symplectically fillable contact structure is non-trivial. In particular, for certain three-manifolds, Heegaard Floer homology gives obstructions to the existence of taut foliations."
    }
